  "prompt": "What do Jews think of John the Baptist?",
  "response": "Jewish perspectives on John the Baptist can vary, but generally, he is a minor figure in Jewish thought compared to his significance in Christian traditions. In Christianity, John the Baptist is revered as a prophet and the forerunner of Jesus Christ, known for baptizing Jesus and preaching repentance. However, in Judaism, there is no particular religious or theological emphasis on him.\n\nJohn the Baptist does not play a role in Jewish religious texts or traditions, as these texts predate his time and do not reference him. Views on him might range from historical acknowledgment as a Jewish preacher and contemporary of Jesus to general indifference, given that his role and teachings did not form part of the development of Judaism. Some Jewish historical scholars may study him in the context of understanding the complex socio-religious landscape of Judea in the early first century CE, but he is not a figure of religious significance within Judaism.",
